      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin misdirection. Let's dive straight into the science of the Maillard reaction. This reaction is a form of non-enzymatic browning that occurs when reducing sugars and amino acids are exposed to heat. It begins at around 140°C (284°F) and accelerates as the temperature rises, peaking at temperatures between 140°C and 165°C (284°F to 329°F). The reaction involves a complex series of chemical changes, including the formation of new compounds that contribute to the flavor, color, and aroma of the crust.\n\nThe Maillard reaction can be broken down into three main stages:\n\n1. The initial stage involves the reaction between a reducing sugar and an amino acid, leading to the formation of a glycosylamine and a molecule of water. This is followed by the Amadori rearrangement, where the glycosylamine rearranges into a ketosamine.\n\n2. The second stage is characterized by the breakdown of the ketosamine into various compounds, including aldehydes, ketones, and other nitrogen-containing molecules. These compounds contribute to the complex flavors and aromas associated with the Maillard reaction.\n\n3. The final stage involves further reactions between these compounds, leading to",
